text:
I received a gift card for $75. I looked at the menu saw they had a paint reconditioning service. Decided I would get this service.....   Let me add my paint is not bad at all. I’ve gotten compliments on how well my paint looks for the year of the car.
Just from calling to make an appointment I wasn’t happy. Apparently when you get this service you have to get a wax coating done. That is an extra $49 dollar charge. I asked if I could do this on my own. Not allowed! So why not just make the service $125 which is came out to!? It’s the gimmick how they bring you in. Okay fine I’ll pay the extra. Upon calling and finding out about these extra charges I made an appointment for 12 o’clock. Arrived 5 minutes early. No parking no attendant/worker to be found. Finally I park near the vacuums then check in.
Didn’t seem to care I had an appointment. Got the same speech I got on the phone “Typically takes 2-21/2 hours some times longer. Okay fine with me 3 hours or so. Nope!! After 4 hours I called and got “your detailer says it will be ready for 4:30” I arrive at 4:30 car is sitting outside looking good. No one around garage doors shut! I do a once around looks decent not going to complain. Yes they pulled some surfaces scratches out but that was about all.
So 41/2 hours later to do a job I could have done at home in about the same time. The following day I had a car show i was attending. Part of why I chosethis service to save me a day of work. I walk out the next morning and start noticed excess wax spots. I work those spots in.
Unfortunately it rained during the car show and in my travels. It’s now two days later there is white all over!! Seems it was rushed.

So my final say is if you are going to get a cut and buff service find a good auto body shop. It will cost you the same. Maybe a little more but it won’t turn out how this has.

I will say after these issues. I did work with the manager and asst manager and got these resolved. so my review remains the same on the work. Customer satisfaction I will give 5 stars

text:
I've had it on my radar for a while but never make it over this way. With most or all items locally sourced you can't help but love this quaint brunch spot. I ordered off the specials menu, the country gravy Benedict with a side of dressed greens, had to get a little greens on my plate ^_^. It was phenomenal. My husband ordered the biscuits and gravy which was also super tasty. Everything on the menu sounded amazing it took us a good 15 minutes to make our final decision. Molly our server was spectacular. Finally got to try Nitro Carts nitro brew and it was heavenly as I hoped it would be. Do yourself a flavor and have brunch, lunch, or dinner here, you wont be disappointed.

Just an FYI they don't have home fries, they're hash browns. For all those home fry lovers like my husband. Don't let the menu fool you.

text: As they say in real estate, location is the key. The Courtyard could not be better situated for ALL needs- convention hall convenience, shopping, attractiveness of the location with the parks, downtown business, and nearby restaurants. Also, the main public bus, Amtrak trains, and the local train to Boston as well as many of the major sites such as Brown University, museums and the small National Park Museum in the downtown area are within walking distance if you can walk uphill. The walk from the Amtrak station is a very easy flat surface sidewalk. You really do not need a car in Providence and so this is a wonderful convenience. The sightseeing trolley will take you all over the city and so you can see the areas that are too far to walk to.

text: If I could give zero stars, I would. I showed up today to pick up my pre-booked standard-sized car. A compact car and a minivan were the only vehicles available. I found not one,  but two severely damaged tires (one with a large bubble, about to burst, and another with several pieces of rubber missing). I had to wait for more than an hour for a tow truck and then return to the airport with the car.  Overall, the process took 2 hours of my time, just to start from square one again at the airport. There was another customer ahead of me complaining that the car they just rented had car seats in the back still and was filled  with trash. text:
This icon of Burlington has seen better days. Yes, Wuhan virus adaptive measures by the state have caused a lot of challenges. But more to my point is that I felt like I was in a protest parade and that every shop was a posterboard for multiple causes.

A word to Merchants: sometimes people just want to shop, not be involuntarily exposed to something they may have already paid a lot of attention to. Many of us just do it because, not because of a sad poster in your window.

I noticed on a few occasions that the strong odor of pot would suddenly make its presence known to my nostrils on turning a corner. During mid-day. But hey, it's legal here so deal with it. That and the skateboarding mid-30's adult who cut between the dining tables where you may be sitting and trying to eat.

No thanks Burlington, we won't miss each other in the future.
